	<div class="section_print">
		<a href="http://www.newwest.net/"><img src="http://www.newwest.net/images/banners/print_friendly_logo.jpg" border="0" style="margin-bottom:40px"></a>
					<h4>Literary Odds & Ends</h4>
		
		<h1>Monday Literary Roundup</h1>
		<h2><i></i></h2>
		<div class="text-feature_print">
							<p>By Jenny Shank, 5-07-07</p>
			
			
							<p>The spirit of Jack Kerouac has been looming large this year, the fiftieth anniversary of <i>On The Road</i>.&nbsp; The original manuscript appeared at the Denver Public Library earlier this year, and is <a target="_blank" href="http://www.newwest.net/index.php/city/article/kerouacs_on_the_road_lands_in_santa_fe/C110/L110/" title="now in Santa Fe">now in Santa Fe</a>.&nbsp; Naropa University, the Boulder college founded by Kerouac&#8217;s beat buddy Allen Ginsberg, is planning to celebrate in a big way, and is gearing up for its Kerouac festival to be held from June 30 to July 1 this summer.&nbsp; In the meantime, Kerouac fans can check out <a target="_blank" href="http://www.naropa.edu/blogs/index.php?blog=2" title="the festival's blog">the festival&#8217;s blog</a>, which includes news, audio, and video on all things related to Kerouac.
</p>
<p>
And for those who just can&#8217;t get enough of Kerouac, NewWest.net reader Michael Hess wrote a comment last week about the various map projects he&#8217;s been working on to geo-locate the places Kerouac wrote about.&nbsp; Hess is <a target="_blank" href="http://littourature.blogspot.com" title="blogging as he maps">blogging as he maps</a>, and the in-progress map <a target="_blank" href="http://www.geocities.com/Athens/4209/map/kerouac_map.htm" title="can be found here">can be found here</a>.&nbsp; Hess also created a Google Earth map, a &#8220;KMZ tour of Sal&#8217;s first journey,&#8221; <a target="_blank" href="http://salsa.fresca.googlepages.com/home" title="available here">available here</a>.
</p>
<p>
There&#8217;s a new event in Boulder for people who enjoy music and essays called <a target="_blank" href="http://myspace.com/tellingstoriesmusic" title="Telling Stories">Telling Stories</a>, that strives to be a sort of homegrown version of This American Life.&nbsp; According to its MySpace site, &#8220;We&#8217;re mixing up essay readings and short chamber music pieces that all fall under a given theme.&#8221;  Writers and storytellers are <a target="_blank" href="http://denver.craigslist.org/wrg/305545779.html" title="invited to submit their essays to">invited to submit their essays to</a> be considered for performance.&nbsp; Marc Shulgold wrote about Telling Stories and its founder, writer/musician Jennie Dorris for <a target="_blank" href="http://www.rockymountainnews.com/drmn/music/article/0,2792,DRMN_54_5479646,00.html" title="the Rocky Mountain News recently">the Rocky Mountain News recently</a>.&nbsp; The next show is at <a target="_blank" href="http://www.mapspotr.com/MapSpotr/index.html?locId=20" title="the Laughing Goat">the Laughing Goat</a> on May 18.
</p>
<p>
For those interested in filmmaking, <a target="_blank" href="http://documentaryinstitute.org/index.php" title="The Documentary Cinema Institute">The Documentary Cinema Institute</a> in Denver is hosting a workshop on May 19 called &#8220;Stories from Times Past: Approaches and Techniques of Historical Filmmaking with Beret Strong, John Tweedy, Felicia Furman.&#8221;  According to a press release, the workshop &#8220;focuses on the making of historical documentaries that are original, meaningful, and skillfully crafted. Presenters will share their experiences of making documentaries that approach historical events from personal perspectives. The class includes viewings that illustrate strategies used in a range of historical films. Areas to be covered include research, funding, narrative techniques, style, archival materials, and music.&#8221;
</p>
<p>
Do you know of more literary happenings in the Rocky Mountain region?&nbsp; If so,  <script type="text/javascript">
